@node "Introduction" "BerzBerch?"
     BERZBENCH (Some Wonderful Patterns for Workbench)

I often desired colorful patterns for my Wb, but I never found anything I
liked. I have often seen fine icon collections, but never some patterns that I
could really like.

 Well... I drew inspiration to the 'Art Déco' Style and BerzBench 1.0 was the
 result. Now I have added some new very cool patterns, so I decided to upload
the new archive to Aminet.


 All the Patterns of BerzBench have been heavily influenced by the marbles and
the decorations in  the Thermae Lorenzo BERZieri (Salsomaggiore Terme ---
Parma --- Italy. If you came around there, please give a look at it!)... so
the name BerzBench.
@endnode

@node "why" "why should I"
Why should I install BerzBench?

Well, I think BerzBench are the best patterns for Workbench I have ever seen.

Give a look at the JPG examples and you will see (and the pictures lose a lot
with the JPG compression...)


This has a cost: the Workbench with AT LEAST 64 colors (and a pair of
BerzBench patterns installed)  becomes a bit slower than usual, though the
BerzBench patterns use a VERY LITTLE MEMORY and are optimized for the BEST
SPEED.

If you used CGWPAttern by Simon Richardson (on Aminet:
util/wb/CGWPattern107.lha), you would not see any difference in speed at
all!!! So if you want the patterns to be mapped faster you should give a look
at it. Even FastIPrefs by Hans-W. Schober is VERY good
(Aminet:util/boot/FastIPrefs4012.lha).
 You could use both CGWPattern and FastIPrefs for best speed.

Try Berzbench! It is great!
@endnode

@node "What you need" "Requirements"
You need:


--- Workbench with at least 64 colors (up to 16 millions... I tested BerzBench
with a 24 bit screen  CybergfX and everything worked fine).

--- WBPattern (it should be in your Workbench/Prefs drawer)

or, better,

--- CGWPattern (faster and more accurate than WBPattern) by Simon Richardson
    (you can find it on Aminet: util/wb/CGWBPattern107.lha)
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Install and use"
 INSTALLATION
 Simply drag the drawer BerzBench in any directory of your HD, maybe
Workbench: Prefs/Presets.


1 --- Set the number of colors of your Workbench Screen to 64 (or more).

2--- Run the program WBPattern (you should find it in your Workbench/ Prefs
drawer). Select a pattern of Berzbench and TEST. The look of your Workbench
will be fairly better.

The possible pattern combinations between Workbench and Windows are around
 900, but the  really cool ones should be around twenty, twenty-five, in my
opinion...

They should be enough for you,  anyway.
@endnode

@node "New" "What's new"
What has changed since BerzBench 1.1c:

--- Added 4 wonderful families of patterns.

--- Removed the Disk- Drawer icons (since no-one seemed to like them)
@endnode

